It's been awhile since we had one of these so some starter questions

last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
>Who is he?
Link, the champion of Hyrule and wielder of the Triforce of Courage.
>What series/source is he from?
Main character of the Legend of Zelda series. He started off with silly designs somewhat based off Peter Pan and eventually morphed into its own when a designer made him sexier as an adult for Ocarina of Time. From here they just kept making the adult versions of him hotter and hotter.
>How do you feel about his series/source?
Probably my favorite game series, with several entries on my favorite games of all time including Majora's Mask in my #1 spot.
>What are some things you love about him?
He's adorable, looks-wise. He's a brave young man with a beautiful toned body, slightly shy but not awkward, and just a good person overall. He stands up for the weak but not in a weird anime hero way, just in the way that a real person would. His silence is part of the charm, confident enough to not have to constantly talk to show his feelings. And the idea of being a traveler in medieval times just lends to all sorts of cool scenarios that could be dreamy or romantic.
>What are some of his favorite things?
Link loves food, all kinds. He loves to be with people and to be helpful. He loves exploring, camping, but also enjoys times to relax in something bougie for a night or two. He loves to sleep in, tucking his arm across your chest before slowly waking up and making breakfast. He loves to go to the bar, get back home, and do all the things he's normally too stoic to do.

In traditional indigenous Ainu marriages, People who marry in their own villages are all called uiriwak, ‘blood relations,’ ‘brethren,’ but those who marry OUTSIDE their villages are called uiritak, i.e. ‘relation taken away,’ or ‘distant relations,’ ‘brethren brought in.’

Soon after marriage the bridegroom makes a knife sheath, a spoon, a shuttle and weaving loom, and presents them to his bride. This little ceremony is called mat-eikara, i.e. ‘making my wife.’ The bride then makes a girdle, a pair of leggings, a necklace, and a head-dress, which she presents to her husband; this is called hoku eikara, i.e. ‘making my husband.’
